WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.840
Sorry. Here are my disclosures. Primary CNS lymphoma is a rare disease, making up less than

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:16.660
1% of all non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and it's a disease of elderly. Median age of diagnosis is mid-60s to

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:23.540
late-60s, and incidence increases sharply with age. It goes from 0.4 to 4 per 100,000 in patients

00:00:23.540 --> 00:00:29.820
over 70 years old. More than 40% of patients are over 70, and more than 20% of patients are

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:35.420
over 80. And age is considered an independent poor prognostic factor in primary CNS lymphoma.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.780
The standard of care treatment right now is to give high-dose methotrexate induction followed

00:00:40.780 --> 00:00:46.700
by transplant. But as I said, a lot of patients that present with primary CNS lymphoma are older

00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:53.160
patients, and they are often transplant ineligible. And right now, there's no standard of care for

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:58.040
transplant ineligible patients. And the consolidation and maintenance approaches that we've been using

00:00:58.040 --> 00:00:59.640
are very heterogeneous.

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:02.520
And the real-world outcomes are very poorly characterized.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:10.520
So I conducted a multi-center retrospective study from 12 academic U.S. centers from 2010 to 2024.

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:16.180
The use of induction therapy was at physician's discretion. The patients that were involved in

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:21.340
the studies were over 18 years old. We limited the study to diffuse large B-cell lymphoma subtype.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:26.840
They had to have been treated with high-dose methotrexate induction or variation of,

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:29.360
and they must have had a stable disease,

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:33.060
or better, post-induction prior to receiving consolidation or maintenance.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:37.420
They were deemed transplant ineligible by the treating physicians, and the primary

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:42.300
outcome endpoint was PFS and looking at different consolidation and maintenance approaches.

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:52.120
Total, 191 patients were included. Median age was 69. About 40% of patients were ECOG2 or higher

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:58.380
with presence of geriatric syndromes. Majority of patients had either motor or cognitive changes.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:04.000
Here's a breakdown of the induction regimen that was used. A third of a patient received MTR,

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:09.480
methotrexate, temozolomide, rituximab. A third received the MPVR, methotrexate,

00:02:09.700 --> 00:02:15.440
procarbazine, vincresine with rituximab. And a third received methotrexate only or with rituximab.

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:22.120
Here's a breakdown of why they were transplant ineligible. A fifth of patients for functional

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:29.100
status. A fifth for age, about 15% for both. A fifth was unknown. And then 15% for both.

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:32.420
And then 15% for preference and small percentage for lack of support.

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:39.520
Here are the consolidations and maintenances that were used for consolidation. Majority of the

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:44.940
regimens were cytarabine-based, either alone or with combination, with etoposide being the most

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:50.060
common regimen that was used with cytarabine. Radiation was another one that was frequently

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:56.140
used. Maintenance was a little bit more broad. There were patients that were treated with

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:59.080
rituximab or high-dose methotrexate. And then there were patients that were treated with

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:04.740
temozolomide, BTK inhibitor, lenalidomide, or some combination thereof. There was a strong

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:09.800
institutional preference for consolidation or maintenance strategies, indicating that there

00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:15.560
isn't really a good standard of care, and that physicians are relying on their past experience.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:19.920
About three-quarters of patients completed intended post-induction therapy.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:28.180
So here is a treatment outcome of all comers, and so everybody that's been treated. PFS was 69 months

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:28.920
and OS was 12 months. So here's a treatment outcome of all comers, and so everybody that's been

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:33.120
treated. PFS was 69 months and OS was 123 months. The first look at this data, I was actually quite

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:37.520
surprised because this was actually much better than I had intended for transplant-ineligible

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:43.460
patients. The induction regimen really made no difference in PFS and OS, although I'm not showing

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:52.580
the data here. Not surprising, but you did see a worse overall survival benefit with lack of CR.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:57.960
So on the left, you see that if you have complete response, you tend to do much better. And if you

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:04.860
had a poor performance status at diagnosis, so if you had the ECOG of one, you did much better than

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:11.800
if you had the ECOG of two or worse. The PFS and OS were very similar between all consolidation

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:19.240
therapies. You can see the blue is etoposide with cytarabine. The red is cytarabine and other

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:25.660
combinations. And then green is radiation. You see that all the lines overlap. The PFS was 62 months

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:31.800
and OS was 95 months. And all the consolidation approaches had similar outcome. And this was the

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:37.100
same for maintenance therapies. There are several maintenance therapies that we've looked at.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:42.380
There were really no differences in their PFS and OS. The PFS with the maintenance approach was

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:48.580
78 months with OS was not reached. But if you look at all the PFS and OS between the

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:54.940
consolidation and maintenance, there really wasn't any differences. What we do know, however,

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:55.640
is that the PFS and OS were very similar. The PFS and OS were very similar. The PFS and OS were

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.040
OS is very short in patients who progress.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:05.880
So about a third of patients relapse or progress, and overall survival after progression was

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:12.640
only 10 months compared to 123 months that we saw in the entire cohort.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.280
About 20% of patients were hospitalized, and not surprisingly, the hospitalization was

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:22.560
higher in patients who got maintenance because you were receiving therapy for a much longer

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:28.160
period of time, and majority of these were infections and febrile neutropedia.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:34.280
So in conclusion, we see that treatments are very heterogeneous and that it is highly institutional

00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:35.420
dependent.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:40.220
There are excellent outcomes even for transplant-ineligible patients with median overall survival over

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:44.660
120 months, and that overall survival was significantly associated with performance

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:47.880
status and depth of response after induction.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:52.540
And what induction you used really did not influence the overall survival.

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:57.720
There was no significant difference between PFS and OS, between consolidation and maintenance

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:02.780
approaches, even if you adjusted for age, sex, ECOG, and response.

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:06.300
The real major unmet need are the people that progress.

00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:09.740
So about a third of patients relapse and progress, and they really had a poor outcome with a

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:12.520
short overall survival of 10 months.

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:17.280
Given that there is really no significant difference between regimens, I think the take-home

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:22.380
point from here is that really we should be deciding on the patient's consolidation or

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:25.980
maintenance regimen based on safety profile.

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:30.100
With that, these are my acknowledgments, and a lot of the collaborators, Adam did a whole

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:32.240
bunch of statistics for us.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.200
Thank you.
